Profit Optimization

Ensemble Models and Bayesian Workflow

Andrej Arpáš

12/15/2020

Problem Setup

Imagine you’re optimizing (maximizing) for profit of some small business. The business has corporate clients (other corporate entities) and you have to decide which are to be targeted in a marketing campaign, the result of which should be a purchase decision on the part of the client. You target them by making a phone call but your call center can only handle calling 1/4 of the client base max. You have two datasets. One with the client base, and one called the pilot (which contains but a subset of the clients). Both contain 20 variables; the former requries making a recommendation (1 or 0) as to whom to target for the purchase, the latter also includes the purchase decisions and provides information about which clients, included in the pilot, were in the treatment group. Other than that, you know nothing about the variables.

One way to proceed is to use the pilot data as training and the client base data as the test set. Make inferences about which company to target and why. I’ll run a number of machine learning models, which, considering we know nothing about the variables, I don’t expect to perform all that well, comparing that approach to a simple Bayesian model in terms of their predictive accuracy and efficacy of making recommendations about which clients to target. The Bayesian model will give us a posterior to work with to gauge the probabilities with which a client would make a purchase decision, which is what we will optimize for.

Okay, what we can do, to start off with, is to run some models to figure out what the variables (vars) were that turned out predictive of a purchase decision based on the pilot.

The idea being that optimizing/maximizing for those vars that perform best would yield us the best candidates for modelling on the remainder of the customer base. (Provided that the sample in “pilot.csv” is representative and statistically sound otherwise, which is one assumption here. If so, we can use it to make inferences about the whole lot.)

EDA

We can attempt some visualizations but since we don’t know what the vars represent, there isn’t much to discern patterns-wise.

We may do at least one ensemble model, so let’s do some prep for that.

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)
out <- train(as.factor(purchase) ~ ., data = training, method = "rpart2",
             tuneLength = 10, trControl = ctrl)
note: only 6 possible values of the max tree depth from the initial fit.
 Truncating the grid to 6 .
plot(out)

So predictably, there are diminishing returns in using all vars. 15 max. should suffice but ideally way fewer.

plot(out$finalModel)
text(out$finalModel, pretty = 0)

y_hat <- predict(out, newdata = testing)
defaultSummary(data.frame(obs = as.factor(testing$purchase), 
                          pred = y_hat))
##  Accuracy     Kappa 
## 0.9050000 0.1106867

Virtually guaranteed to overfit in the training data, and underperform on the test data, by default; these results, however, seem pretty good. Confirming the hypothesis is the fact that performing tree pruning to hone in on “the best” parts of the original tree simply returns the root, so this seems already the most optimal tree.

Modelling

Let’s proceed to modelling and see if we can figure out what vars matter the most using some actual architectures. We can also do the modelling using tidymodels has a few extra wrinkels though, so let’s do the train_test_split the tidymodels way to avoid clashes.

base_recipe <- recipe(buybool ~ ., data = purchase_train) %>% prep
tree_model <- decision_tree(mode = "classification", cost_complexity = 0.006) %>% set_engine("rpart") # cp = 0.01 as a default. Too high here.
tree_wflow <- workflow() %>% add_model(tree_model) %>%
  add_formula(buybool ~ V18 + V16 + V8 + V4) # Some weak correlations.
tree_fit <- fit(tree_wflow, data = bake(base_recipe, NULL))

plot(tree_fit$fit$fit$fit)
text(tree_fit$fit$fit$fit, pretty = 0)

Get a confusion matrix implied by the model in the test set.

The predictiveness is atrocious and the results confirm what the visualizations intimated all along, which is that these vars do not seem terribly predictive of the purchase deicison. Conditional on the model and the data, that is. Since we want an ensamble model, we grudgingly oblige but I’m not happy about this. That said, let’s do Boosting, and see if we can do better.

Boosting

We still try to minimize the sum-of-squared residuals but in lieu of calculating the difference between the outcome and the strata-means, boosting calculates the difference between the residuals from earlier stages of the tree and the strata-means.

So far, we “got away with” factors/characters since rpart/tidymodels can handle that. For boosting, we need a sparse matrix. Let’s do a quick fix.

f <- data.frame(lapply(e, function(x) as.numeric(x)))
f$buybool <- e$buybool

purchase_split_ <- initial_split(f, prob = 0.75, strata = buybool)
purchase_train_ <- training(purchase_split_)
purchase_test_ <- testing(purchase_split_)
boost_recipe <- recipe(buybool ~ ., data = purchase_train_) %>% prep
boost_model <- boost_tree() %>% 
  set_engine("xgboost", nthreads = parallel::detectCores()) %>% 
  set_mode("classification")
boost_wflow <- workflow() %>% add_recipe(boost_recipe) %>% add_model(boost_model)

cv_ <- vfold_cv(bake(boost_recipe, NULL)) # 10-fold crosval.

fit_boost <- fit_resamples(boost_wflow, cv_,
                           control = control_resamples(verbose = FALSE,
                                                       save_pred = TRUE))

Doesn’t perform terrifically either. The trouble is that we have a lot of predictors and not a whole lot of observations. Nearest Shrunken Centroids (NSC) is a method that normally is quite well suited to such tasks. Let’s try that.

These are the best results so far. There is significant sparseness in the dataset on account of ~8% purchase decisions only in the pilot. That doesn’t bode particularly well for models to learn on. Adding bells and whistles to fine-tune the QDA doesn’t shave off more false negatives. So we have our best performer.

Back to Purchases

Let’s use the best model to predict purchases.

h <- read.csv("CustomerBase.csv")
h <- subset(h, select = -c(V2, V18, V19)) # Use for predict.

g_ <- subset(g, select = -c(treatment))

QDA Again

QDA_ <- train(purchase ~ .,
              data = g_, method = "qda", preProcess = c("center", "scale"))
pred <- as.data.frame(predict(QDA_, newdata = h))
colnames(pred)[1] <- "pred"
h_pred <- cbind(h, pred)
h_pred$pred <- as.numeric(as.character(factor(h_pred$pred, labels = 1:0, levels = c("yes", "no"))))

Does this look reasonable? Shouldn’t have vastly more or less buys, as a fraction of the total, than we did in the pilot. It’s uncannily on target. Again, bear in mind that there are a lot of assumptions. We assume that the pilot was properly randomized and that the sampling was representative of the lot. We further condition on the model and the rest of the data. This also tells us that the model didn’t learn all that much on the training data (pilot).

Seeing the model expects only 7,859 purchases and our call center capacity is 1/4 of the client base (23,750), we can call all our targets and will still have a buffer. Now, provided that we have already paid for the capacity/bandwidth, we might as well use it, though this is a speculation, in which case we could lower the probabilty threshold for the model from .5 to something smaller, which isn’t advisable if we can avoid it, which in most cases we can. Should we have the opposite, i.e. more candidates than spots/capacity in the call center, we could do stan_clogit to yield a posterior with probabilities for who is the most likely to purchase and call them in the order of the likelihood. Honestly, our output suggests that machine learning (ML) doesn’t really promote thinking. It’s useful, but what you really want is to understand your variables, do some proper modelling, ideally Bayesian, and perform statistical data analysis on your variables to prune them and in order to make hypotheses. You can in fact do everything purely Bayesian and have better predictions. Which is exactly what I’m going to show you next. We know nothing about our variables though, so it won’t be as effective as it should but my guess is that it will still predict better than ML. Okay, so next up, Bayes.

stan_glm

One of the simpler models that is well suited to classification tasks though.

options(mc.cores = parallel::detectCores())
set.seed(42)

Let’s look at those correlations once more and we’re off to the races.

df <- subset(g, select = -c(treatment)) # Drop non-numeric, zero variance vars.
df$purchase <- as.numeric(as.character(factor(df$purchase, labels = 1:0, levels = c("yes", "no"))))
corrplot(cor(df))

x <- model.matrix(purchase ~ . - 1, data = df) # -1 meaning all but "y".
y <- df$purchase

# Degrees of freedom (`df`) in `student_t` are 1 as a default, which is identical to `cauchy`, so just move that. Default otherwise.
t_prior <- student_t(df = 2, location = 0, scale = 2.5) # Uninformative prior.
fit <- stan_glm(purchase ~ ., data = df,
                family = binomial(link = "logit"), 
                prior = t_prior, prior_intercept = t_prior,
                QR = TRUE) # Recommended for computational reasons when there are multiple predictors.
round(posterior_interval(fit, prob = 0.9), 2)

PSIS-LOO result seems reliable enough with all Pareto k estimates less than 0.7.

linpred <- posterior_linpred(fit)
preds_ <- posterior_linpred(fit, transform = TRUE)
pred_ <- colMeans(preds_)
pr <- as.integer(pred_ >= 0.5)

round(mean(xor(pr, as.integer(y==0))), 2) # Accuracy.
## [1] 0.92
truth <- df$purchase

u_ <- union(pr, truth)
t_ <- table(factor(pr, u_), factor(truth, u_),
            dnn = c("pr", "truth"))

colnames(t_) <- c("no", "yes")
rownames(t_) <- c("no", "yes")

Do note that (i), off the bat, the simplest Bayesian model outperforms ML, and (ii) it performs especially better with respect to false positives, i.e. it captures far more of the real purchases than anything we tried before. Therefore, let’s use this model to predict the overall purchases instead.

ytilde <- posterior_predict(fit, newdata = h, draws = 1000)
dim(ytilde)
[1]  1000 95000
pr2 <- colMeans(ytilde)
pr3 <- ifelse(pr2 >.5, 1, 0)
sum(pr3) # ~15 hundred purchases only.
[1] 1555

So, if we want to do this “old school”, and specify a .5 probability threshold, we generate a binary outcome, purchase / no purchase, but that doesn’t necessarily make a whole lot of sense. Furthermore, doing so gives us merely around 15 hundred “buys”, whereas what we ideally want is to identify up to 23,750 targets for our marketing campaign that would generate those purchases. Indeed, we do Bayes because we want to avail ourselves of the power of posterior distributions and the probabilistic nature of the models. Therefore, what I suggest is to look at the means of the probabilities from 1,000 draws from the posterior distribution, order them from highest to smallest, and identify 23,750 of the highest ones in descending order.

dec <- as.data.frame(pr2) # Decisions.
dec_ <- dec %>% arrange(desc(pr2)) #%>% head(n = 15)
dec_$company_name <- rownames(dec_)
rownames(dec_) <- NULL
dec_$pr2[1:23750] <- 1
dec_$pr2[23751:nrow(dec_)] <- 0
pr_final <- dec %>% arrange(desc(pr2))
dec_$prob <- pr_final$pr2
colnames(dec_)[1] <- c("decision")
colnames(dec_)
## [1] "decision"     "company_name" "prob"
dec_final <- dec_ %>% arrange(as.numeric(as.character(company_name)))
dec_final %>% head(n = 15) %>% tibble()

Conclusion and Final Output

What we have is a data frame / Excel document with the clients ordered the way expected, with the recommended decision and probability with which that client will make a purchase adjacent, conditional on the data and the model. This is a much better approach, in my estimation, than regular ML.
